> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>This is the 2nd chapter in the Mothball &amp; Fafner story, picking up right after &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub169.ezboard.com/fmtboardsfrm11.showMessage?topicID=38.topic" target="top">Last Train To Halas</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;. This is a somewhat long chapter, so I'll be posting it in parts for easier reading.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>A Wood Elf, a Dwarf, and a Barbarian Walk Into a Bar</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
We emerged from the Blackburrow tunnels, breathing hard from the terror-filled run. As dawn's light illuminated the hills, we immediately spotted a bear not far from the tunnel's entrance. An odd stagger to his gait and foam from his mouth put us instantly on our guard. I stashed my torch and tightly gripped the fine steel great staff looted from the giant, while Mothball drew her sword from scabbard.<br>
<br>
The bear did not amble off, as most do, but reared into the air on his hindquarters and charged us. I blinded him with a flash of light; Mothball bashed him with her shield while swiping at his belly. His mass nearly toppled her as he dropped downwards, and I swung the staff across his side to knock him away. The beast's cries of anger and pain echoed the hills as he tried to claw away the shield holding him back from his prey. Moth's sword stabbed deep into his chest as I landed a blow upon his back, and his attacks ceased while his cries echoed on.<br>
<br>
&quot;Quick - some of the rangers here abhor all violence against these beasts, even those maddened by disease - we must go&quot;, I urged. Despite our exhaustion, we were on the run again, coated with bear's blood.<br>
<br>
&quot;You know these lands then?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aye. Many a time I've journeyed to Qeynos or the fishing huts in West Karanas, on errands for Teria O'Danos or Jinkus Felligan&quot;. I neglected to mention that I still got lost if I wandered too far from the roads - my sense of direction has never been the keenest and my memory abysmal.<br>
<br>
We dashed across this hills, to the road, past the Sayer's hut, past the stone markers, and through Qeynos's gates. We could rest here before the long journey ahead. Besides, I had hoped that my elven companion might be able to purchase an item which I could not: a spell to enable my eyes to see in the night as her's did, ending the need for cumbersome lanterns and lights.<br>
<br>
I should also send a message off to mom so that she'd know that I survived the ice giant incident. She would worry, she always did. The tundra frightened her, or rather, me in the tundra frightened her. I feared my planned trip to Freeport would not be easy on her. But I was of age; such journeys from home were my right, almost a duty. Well, almost of age. I could leave a message for her at the Qeynos bank of my whereabouts - in the regular exchanges between Qeynos and Halas, she would get word. I wondered if Mothball had family in Kelethin who wondered where she was. But it seemed too personal a question to ask.<br>
<br>
We sold off the ice giant items and stocked up on provisions for the journey ahead. I reluctantly parted with a fine steel mace to gain the coins needed for the spell. Mothball showed off the handmade backpack she purchased from a halfling at the gates. We made our way through the town - in my eagerness to procure the spell, I had to force myself to pause at the corners for her. Apparently she noticed.<br>
<br>
&quot;You're very sweet to always wait for me&quot;, she said with a sly smile.<br>
<br>
&quot;Err, ahhh&quot;, I stammered.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've never seen a barbarian turn that color&quot;, she snickered, but in a kindly way.<br>
<br>
The stammering increased.<br>
<br>
&quot;You, Halas-man!&quot;, interrupted some oaf, &quot;There's another one of your kind at Fish Ale's. Said that if I saw one of you traveling with a female wood elf in orange armor I should send you his way. Said there would be a pint of ale in it for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;McCleary!&quot;, we said in unison, dashing off in the direction he pointed. Moth tossed him a few silver pieces - I was too eager to give it in any thought. We rushed through the streets, me in the lead, till we reached a tavern near the docks. Throwing open the door, I almost ran head on into a mountain of a man who stood blocking the passageway. At the bar was the presumed-dead McCleary, somehow having managed to survive being stomped to death by an ice giant.<br>
<br>
He was mid-argument with a dwarf, the ne'er-to-do Trump, who suddenly drew a dagger just as Moth and I shouted &quot;McCleary!&quot;. McCleary was startled to hear his name, and Trumpy got in an easy jab during the distraction. Instinctively, I called upon the healing powers of the Tribunal.<br>
<br>
The bar erupted with cries for guards. Barstomper the bouncer hit me from behind so hard I could scarcely see, breathe, or stand. In adjunct terror, I fled from the bar with him in pursuit. Down the docks, faster, faster, not daring to look behind. The sail from a great ship billowed as it sped near, and I dove off the edge of the pier.<br>
<br>
But I didn't swim towards the ship. Rather, I dove down, to a secret sewer entrance, that I had heard rumors of. Hopefully the deception would fool my pursuer. It was nearly impossible to see anything down here - my vision wasn't good enough, and I regretted not having gotten the night vision spell before going to meet McCleary in the bar. Finally, I spotted an even darker hole amongst the the murk, and within it, an iron grate. I pushed it open, swam down, then up, and finally...air.<br>
<br>
